href="http://tipnut.com/tips-for-leftovers/#comment-43031"> June 24, 2008 at 9:08 am</a></div><p>You can also freeze apples to make applesauce &#8211; just simmer until soft, then mash and strain out the core/peel.</p><p>Have only a couple spoonfuls of rice, meat and veggies left?  Put them in a large plastic container in the freezer. Add to it after each meal &#8211; little of this, little of that.  Make soup or a nice casserole with them when the container is full.</p><p>Bones from a meal can be saved to use for soup stock.</p><p>In my old cookbook (1944) there are a few ways listed for using leftovers &#8211; mix with thick white sauce or mashed potato, breaded and fry, &#8216;scalloped&#8217; with bread crumbs, white sauce and baked, or creamed/pureed.  Even just a half cup or so of leftover veggies can be used in this manner.</p><p>Equal parts mashed potato and cooked chicken/fish make great patties when breaded &amp; fried too!</p><div
class="reply"> <a
class='comment-reply-link' href='/tips-for-leftovers/?replytocom=43031#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-43031", "43031", "respond", "1211")'>Reply</a></div></div></li><li
