class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-60282"><div
id="div-comment-60282" class="comment-body"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><cite
class="fn">Jen</cite> <span
class="says">says:</span></div><div
class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a
href="http://tipnut.com/tips-for-leftovers/#comment-60282"> March 5, 2009 at 11:24 pm</a></div><p>leftovers (salmon, ham, bacon, broccoli etc.) can easily be thrown into a quiche and turned into another meal. I mix leftovers with 3 eggs, 1/4 cup cream, 1 cup grated cheese and some salt and pepper and pour into to a pre-made frozen pie shell and bake at 350 for about an hour. Cooked quiche can be frozen (after cooled) for about 2 months.</p><div
class="reply"> <a
class='comment-reply-link' href='/tips-for-leftovers/?replytocom=60282#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-60282", "60282", "respond", "1211")'>Reply</a></div></div></li><li
class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-75568"><div
id="div-comment-75568" class="comment-body"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><cite
class="fn">Marie Dyde</cite> <span
class="says">says:</span></div><div
class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a
href="http://tipnut.com/tips-for-leftovers/#comment-75568"> August 14, 2010 at 8:08 am</a></div><p>Any tips for using surplus lemon rind/shells after juicing?</p><div
class="reply"> <a
class='comment-reply-link' href='/tips-for-leftovers/?replytocom=75568#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-75568", "75568", "respond", "1211")'>Reply</a></div></div></li><li
class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-76023"><div
id="div-comment-76023" class="comment-body"><div
class="comment-author vcard"><cite
class="fn">Misty Skye</cite> <span
class="says">says:</span></div><div
class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a
href="http://tipnut.com/tips-for-leftovers/#comment-76023"> August 23, 2010 at 1:16 pm</a></div><p>I use lemon rind for lemon rice pilaf (with celery and bacon), and other dishes. Use rinds in cakes and cookies, or in tea ice cubes.</p><p>I bake my bread heels at a low temp in the oven for breadcrumbs which are used up very quickly. I season my own italian style crumbs with herbs and parmesian and romano.</p><p>Left over cubed ham is great in potato soup, breakfast tacos and quiche. same for bacon.</p><p>Leftover taco meat, I store for chili or make the batch in the crockpot the same night and freeze in serving size containers.</p><p>I flash freeze ANY thing that I make to help from sticking together. I love to flash freeze my meatballs for later meals, and often make VERY LARGE pots of red sauce to freeze as well. I use my frozen green peppers and homegrown tomatoes for this and pizza sauce. And I often freeze pork tenderloin or pork roast in the sauce. It is fall apart tender! YUM</p><p>I like to flash freeze surplus cookie dough, pizza dough, and dinner rolls for convenience. As well as all fruits and veggies. laying food on a cookie sheet to freeze before repackaging really makes a big difference in storage.</p><p>Great tips!</p><div
